So, what we want to
do is cut it to a length

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:38.200
so that it easily reaches when
my arm is bent or straightened out.

00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:39.180
All right.

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:42.100
Straight, bent, both ways.

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:44.280
That hose reaches just fine.

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:46.120
In order to dump the propane out,

00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:47.920
we need to be able
to activate the solenoid.

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:51.400
And to do that, we have
our battery pack of course.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:54.220
So we need somewhere
to put the battery pack.

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:57.620
I've got some space up here
in between the propane tanks,

00:03:57.620 --> 00:04:00.000
and it seems like it would
be a shame to waste that.

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:04.120
So I'm gonna see if I can't
attach our battery pack up here.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:10.580
[Music]

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:11.530
There we go.

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:13.200
That's held nicely in place.

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:17.500
We're gonna take apart this umbrella
and use the spring-loaded metal bars

00:04:17.509 --> 00:04:21.609
as a sort of extending arm
and try and make our prongs

00:04:21.609 --> 00:04:23.140
reach out onto the front of that

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:26.440
so all of the electricity is just
a good distance in front of our arm.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:28.560
That way there shouldn't
be any fire on our hand,

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:31.180
there shouldn't be any
taser leads on our hands.

00:04:31.189 --> 00:04:33.500
It should just be safer all around.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:35.360
[whistling]

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:40.800
Okay, I think I need to
completely destroy this umbrella.

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:43.300
The umbrella mechanism
is pretty simple here.

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:46.620
We've got one metal rod that
fits closely inside of another one.

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:49.640
There's a lock that doesn't
move until you press down on that.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:50.300
Collapses down.

00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:53.080
Normally what holds it in the down
position to some other hardware

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:54.260
that I've already stripped off.

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:57.319
We do have these little barbs down here.

00:04:57.319 --> 00:04:58.830
But they don't latch on
to anything at the moment.

00:04:58.830 --> 00:05:01.780
So what I need to do is cut
a hole in the metal right here

00:05:01.780 --> 00:05:03.520
so that it'll little hook on to those.

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:05.900
That way when I push
this button, it should spring out.

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:08.160
[Music]

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:10.979
We've got the hole cut well filed in.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.520
So now we can bring this back,

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:15.780
and it latches into place.

00:05:15.780 --> 00:05:17.560
And when we push this button down,

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:20.360
it shoots forward.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:22.740
As you saw, it's quite difficult
to push that button down.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:25.640
This spike is a little more
intense than we need it to be.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:28.440
So once again we'll gonna the file,
we're gonna keep the spike there.

00:05:28.449 --> 00:05:29.449
We're gonna shorten it,

00:05:29.449 --> 00:05:31.340
so we don't have to push
quite so hard on this button.

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:33.900
[Music]

00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:36.870
Here is what we're going to use
to extend those taser diodes.

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:40.860
I have these two leads that have
sort of a ceramic non-conductive back,

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:42.860
and of course the metal up front.

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:46.920
At the back of these leads,
I have soldered on these two wires,

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:50.620
and covered the backs
in some liquid electrical tape.

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:54.319
And I'm now actually going to put
several more layers of stuff over that

00:05:54.319 --> 00:05:56.919
to make absolutely sure
that the electricity isn't going

00:05:56.919 --> 00:05:59.260
to try and arc between
the wires back here,

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:01.600
and that it really sticks
to the leads where I want it.

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:04.849
We're also going to attach these
onto the front of this telescoping rod,

00:06:04.849 --> 00:06:08.650
And now need to drill a hole big
enough for the screw to fit in,

00:06:08.650 --> 00:06:11.300
and I'm then going to
add some proto putty.

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:13.700
Just some silicone
mixed up with some water,

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:16.640
and maybe a little bit of cornstarch
to just build up around here.

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:23.660
Now, if we attach this
umbrella bar right about here,

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:25.460
we should be able to press this button,

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:29.680
and it will extend automatically.

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:33.080
So we need to attach
the umbrella bar onto the frame.

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:35.979
To do that, we've got
a hole drilled right here.

00:06:35.979 --> 00:06:39.540
We'll drill a hole into this,
and use a bolt to hold that in place.

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:45.760
[Music]

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.860
All right, this arm is
attached on one side,

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:49.969
