support on the other.

00:06:49.969 --> 00:06:52.280
So what I think we're
gonna do is take this eyebolt.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.140
We will attach that onto the front
of the frame right about here,

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.020
and that will just sort of
be a spot where this can rest.

00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:03.480
And we'll then tighten this bolt down
once we have an angle we want.

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:06.360
And the advantage of the eyebolt
is that it should hold it in place,

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:10.060
and as it extends outward,
it should be able to slide along that.

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:11.280
Still giving a little bit of support,

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:13.920
but without gripping it
so it doesn't slide easily.

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:30.480
[Music]

00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:32.020
That's what we're looking for.

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:36.640
I needed a handle to be able to control
both the gas and electricity at once.

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:38.840
This was originally part
of a wrist rocket,

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:43.029
and I thought I could repurpose it
to be my little double trigger handle.

00:07:43.029 --> 00:07:45.471
So what I've done is
cut three holes into it.

00:07:45.471 --> 00:07:47.780
I've got a rectangle hole
that I cut in right here,

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.699
and then I've got two more holes
that I drilled down in the bottom.

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:52.480
And then it already had
one hole in the top

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:54.300
that happened to be just the right size.

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:57.160
So what we've got is a couple
of different kinds of switches.

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:00.760
So this switch is designed to
do something rather particular.

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:02.220
You can have electricity going into it,

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:05.220
and you can have something
that is activated by the switch,

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:07.540
and then something that is always on.

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:09.660
The second wire is the one
you want to be conditional.

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.540
We are actually not going
to be using this wire,

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:14.620
the one that is always on.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:16.760
So we're just going to cut that off.

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:20.960
Now this switch can mount inside
the rectangle hole that I cut out.

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:24.600
And if I leave enough space,
I can still click it.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:26.700
We've also got this little
push button switch.

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:30.420
Both switches only allow electricity to
flow through as the button is held down.

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:33.378
This one I'm gonna put on top and
it's gonna be the activation for the taser,

00:08:33.380 --> 00:08:35.320
and then pulling
the trigger will drop the fuel.

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:37.260
Beautiful.

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:39.480
We now have two separate
switches we can activate.

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:40.880
Click click click click.

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:44.660
Let's use a couple more zip ties
to attach our switches

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:46.360
to this other piece of aluminum.

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:57.660
[Music]

